## Trends – the Red List Index

The trend in spider extinction risk was measured using a global standard indicator, the IUCN Red List Index (RLI) of species [@butchart2004a]. The RLI is calculated for each taxonomic group based on genuine changes in Red List categories over time. The RLI value ranges from 0 to 1. At a value of 1, all species are at low risk of extinction (Least Concern), while a value of 0 indicates that all species are extinct. The RLI value for spiders in South Africa was calculated in 2020 and included 2 214 species. The RLI value is 0.994, and relative to other taxon groups assessed in South Africa, spiders have the highest RLI value (@fig-3). Since only one assessment has been conducted for spiders, it is not possible to determine the trend in extinction risk for this group. It is important to note that many Data Deficient species are included in the assessment, and hence there is still a high level of uncertainty associated with this result.


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
